			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1935">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>It&rsquo;s always good to be in a writer&rsquo;s target audience, but sometimes disconcerting to be in the center of the bullseye. Like Joseph Bathanti [&ldquo;<a href="/article/540">Half of What I Say Is Meaningless</a>,&rdquo; July 2003], I was born in 1953, played war as a kid, was confused about my stance on Vietnam, and drew a low number (sixty-eight) in the draft lottery. Unlike Bathanti, I had dropped out of college (too much recreation, not enough Recreation and Wildlife Management) and was working in a motorhome factory while I waited for Selective Service to harvest me.</p>

<p>I began basic training in October 1972, and when the presidential election rolled around the following month, my drill sergeant informed us that we could vote only for Nixon, our commander in chief. Since any argument about constitutional rights would have ended up with me dropping and giving him fifty pushups, I decided not to vote.</p>

<p>I was studiously ignoring my air-defense artillery training in El Paso, Texas, when the news arrived about the end of the draft. Those of us who&rsquo;d been on the cusp felt both elated and cheated. We wondered over joints and beers if the army might just admit they&rsquo;d made a mistake and let us out. No such luck. I had twenty months to go.</p>

<p>I was released three months early in exchange for joining the National Guard for a year. Although I&rsquo;d been a sad sack stoner of a soldier, I had a clean record and therefore received a certificate of appreciation &mdash; signed by Richard M. Nixon himself just weeks before he skated out of office. I framed the certificate, hung it next to the toilet, and affixed a label that read, &ldquo;In case of emergency, break glass.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Besides the education and housing benefits, the best perk of being a veteran is that you can criticize, loudly and with impunity, the country&rsquo;s military gaffes, along with yellow ribbons, flag decals, and all other patriotic crap. Or, as they might say down at the local American Legion, &ldquo;Back off. He&rsquo;s one of us .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. the commie bastard.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I thoroughly appreciated Bathanti&rsquo;s look back at those years, and if he ever writes a book about them, I&rsquo;ll buy a copy &mdash; provided there isn&rsquo;t an American flag on the dust jacket.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Ken Kittleson<br>Sparta, Wisconsin</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

